The `testing` function handler is called asynchronously, every time that the button is clicked.

Differently, the `inputValue` variable is evaluated once when the code is firstly executed, at page bootstrap, and never again. The input value gets stored inside the variable and it never gets updated after that (strings are immutable in javascript, once you store a string in a variable, it won&#39;t change unless you assign that variable to another value).

If you want to refresh the value every time you click the button, you have to query the element all the times:

     const testing = () =&gt; {
        const inputValue = (document.getElementById(&quot;inputField&quot;)).value;
        alert(inputValue);
     }

Or you can keep just a reference to the element and query the `value` all the times:

     const inputElement = document.getElementById(&quot;inputField&quot;);
     const testing = () =&gt; alert(inputElement.value);

