This is because the `class` by default makes your code use [strict mode](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1335851/what-does-use-strict-do-in-javascript-and-what-is-the-reasoning-behind-it/1335881#1335881). Normally, [the value of `this` will be assigned to the global object (`window`) if not determined](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3127429/how-does-the-this-keyword-work) but in strict mode, it&#39;s set to `undefined` to prevent accidental problems like using properties of the global object:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function sayName() {
      console.log(&quot;Hello, my name is &quot; + this.name + &quot;!&quot;);
    }

    function sayNameStrict() {
      &quot;use strict&quot;;
      console.log(&quot;Hello, my name is &quot; + this.name + &quot;!&quot;);
    }

    let obj = {
      name: &quot;Fred&quot;,
      sayName: sayName,
      sayNameStrict: sayNameStrict
    }

    obj.sayName(); //this = obj, this.name = &quot;Fred

    sayName(); //this = window, this.name = window.name

    obj.sayNameStrict(); //this = obj, this.name = &quot;Fred

    sayNameStrict(); //this = undefined, this.name = TypeError

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

So, if you execute your second piece of code in strict mode, you&#39;ll get the same outcome as the ES6 class:





